  "prompt": "What are some lesser-known sights to see when visiting Darbhanga, Bihar, India?",
  "response": "Darbhanga, located in the northern part of Bihar, is known for its rich cultural heritage and historical significance. While many people are familiar with its major attractions, such as the Darbhanga Fort and the Maharaja Lakshmishwar Singh Museum, there are several lesser-known sights worth exploring:\n\n1. **Ahilya Khand**: This is a beautiful and relatively lesser-known site with historical significance. It includes a serene pond and is surrounded by lush greenery, ideal for a peaceful outing.\n\n2. **Rajnagar Palace**: Located a short distance from Darbhanga, this palace was once the residence of the Maharajas of Darbhanga. Although in ruins, its architecture and surroundings are breathtaking and offer a glimpse into the grandeur of the past.\n\n3. **Kelab Kothi**: An old colonial building that reflects the historical architecture of the area. It\u2019s not widely visited by tourists but presents a good opportunity for photography and exploration.\n\n4. **Shah Hamaadani Dargah**: This lesser-known dargah is dedicated to a revered Sufi saint and is a tranquil spot reflecting the historical and cultural diversity of the region.\n\n5. **Kankali Mandir**: Situated on the outskirts of Darbhanga, this temple is dedicated to Goddess Kali and is less frequented by tourists. It offers a peaceful environment and is surrounded by nature.\n\n6. **Manchhar Lake**: A beautiful and beautiful natural site perfect for birdwatching and enjoying the scenic views. It is a great place for nature enthusiasts and offers a calm atmosphere.\n\n7. **Nahar Kuan**: A quaint water tank that dates back to the time of the Darbhanga kings. Its historical relevance and serene surroundings make it a lesser-known yet enriching visit.\n\n8. **Sidhivinyak Mandir**: Dedicated to Lord Ganesha, this temple is not often crowded and provides a spiritual experience along with an opportunity to learn about local customs and traditions.\n\n9. **Maharaja College**: A prominent educational institution that boasts of colonial architecture and a rich history, yet remains under the radar for many tourists.\n\n10. **Local Markets**: Exploring local markets such as the Darbhanga Mandi can provide an authentic Bihar experience, where you can find handloom products, local food items, and traditional crafts.\n\nThese sites not only offer a break from the mainstream tourist spots but also provide insights into the culture, history, and everyday life in Darbhanga.",
